220	### 1.5 Rounding Mode Specification
221	
222	All floating-point rounding in NumberInput and Slider MUST use **round-half-up** (standard arithmetic rounding) as the rounding mode. This is the `RoundingMode::HalfUp` equivalent: if the digit being dropped is exactly 5, round away from zero.
223	
224	**Rationale**: Banker's rounding (`round-half-even`) is used in financial accounting to minimize cumulative bias, but it produces counterintuitive results for end users (e.g., `2.5` rounds to `2`, not `3`). Interactive UI components prioritize user expectation over statistical properties.
225	
226	```rust
227	/// Round `value` to `precision` decimal places using round-half-up.
228	fn round_to_precision(value: f64, precision: Option<u32>) -> f64 {
229	    match precision {
230	        Some(p) => {
231	            let factor = 10_f64.powi(p as i32);
232	            (value * factor + 0.5_f64.copysign(value)).trunc() / factor
233	        }
234	        None => value,
235	    }
236	}
237	```
238	
239	| Input   | Precision | Result | Explanation                |
240	| ------- | --------- | ------ | -------------------------- |
241	| `2.5`   | 0         | `3`    | Half rounds up             |
242	| `-2.5`  | 0         | `-3`   | Half rounds away from zero |
243	| `0.105` | 2         | `0.11` | Half-up at 3rd decimal     |
244	| `0.115` | 2         | `0.12` | Half-up at 3rd decimal     |
245	| `1.005` | 2         | `1.01` | Half-up at 3rd decimal     |
246	
247	**Application Order**: Precision rounding is applied AFTER clamping to min/max but BEFORE storing in Context.
248	
